question: When does the function reach its local maximum?
answer: The function \( f(u_1, u_2) \) reaches its local maximum at the point where the gradient of the function is zero. This can be determined by looking at the contour lines on the graph. The contour lines represent points where the value of the function \( f(u_1, u_2) \) is constant. The point where these contour lines intersect is where the function has a local maximum. In this case, the local maximum occurs when \( u_1 = 0 \) and \( u_2 = 0 \).
